1 Introduction

This tutorial demonstrates how to use the lmbayes package to perform (empirical) Bayes estimation in a time-series regression setting. We will use the child_growth dataset from the doBy package, which contains longitudinal height measurements for children. You need a recent version of doBy which is available on github.

2 Load Data and Visualize

We start by loading the data and visualizing the growth trajectories

dat <- doBy::child_growth
dat |> ggplot(aes(age,height, group=subject, color=subject)) + 
  geom_line() + facet_grid(~gender) + theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

We will focus on the boys for this tutorial.

  1. For the first 10 boys we will fit a quadratic model to the height data.

  2. We will then use the regression coefficients to estimate a prior distribution for the coefficients.

  3. We will then use this prior to combine with the likelihood for another boy for which we only have early data.

3 Fit Quadratic Models to Training Data

boy.dat  <- dat |> filter(gender=="boy")
sub <- boy.dat$subject |> unique()
train <- boy.dat |> filter(subject %in% sub[1:10])
train |> ggplot(aes(age,height, group=subject, color=subject)) + 
  geom_line() + facet_grid(~gender) + theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
fit.list <- train |> lm_by(height ~ age + I(age^2) |subject, data=_)

3.1 There is a new kid in town

If we know data for the first, say 5 years, how well can we predict the height for the next years?

this  <- boy.dat |> filter(subject %in% sub[11])
time.early <- 5
this.early <- this |> filter(age <= time.early)
this |>
    ggplot(aes(age,height, group=subject, color=subject)) + geom_line()

3.2 Bayesian Linear Regression: Joint and Conditional Distributions

We assume the following model:

  • The prior on the regression coefficients is
    \[ b \sim \mathcal{N}(m, C) \] where \(m\) is a \(p\)-dimensional mean vector and \(C\) is a \(p \times p\) covariance matrix.

  • The observation model is
    \[ y \mid b \sim \mathcal{N}(Xb, \sigma^2 I) \] where \(X\) is an \(n \times p\) design matrix, \(y\) is an \(n\)-dimensional response vector, and \(\sigma^2\) is the residual variance.

3.2.1 Marginal Distribution of \(y\)

By integrating out \(b\), the marginal distribution of \(y\) is: \[ y \sim \mathcal{N}(X m, X C X^T + \sigma^2 I) \]

3.2.2 Joint Distribution of \((y, b)\)

The joint distribution of \(y\) and \(b\) is multivariate normal: \[ \begin{pmatrix} b \\\\ y \end{pmatrix} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \begin{pmatrix} m \\\\ X m \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} C & C X^T \\\\ X C & X C X^T + \sigma^2 I \end{pmatrix} \right) \]

3.2.3 Conditional Distribution of \(b \mid y\)

From the properties of the multivariate normal, the conditional distribution of \(b\) given \(y\) is: \[ b \mid y \sim \mathcal{N}(m^*, C^*) \] where: \[ m^* = m + C X^T (X C X^T + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} (y - X m) \] \[ C^* = C - C X^T (X C X^T + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} X C \]

3.2.4 Interpretation via \(\Lambda\)

Let \[ \Lambda = C X^T (X C X^T + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} \] so that the posterior mean becomes: \[ m^* = m + \Lambda (y - X m) \]

This form reveals how the prior is updated in the direction of the observed data, scaled by \(\Lambda\) — the influence of the data increases as \(\sigma^2\) decreases or \(C\) becomes less informative.

3.2.5 Simplified Forms via Woodbury Identity

The expressions for the posterior mean and covariance can be simplified using the Woodbury matrix identity: \[ (A + UCV)^{-1} = A^{-1} - A^{-1} U (C^{-1} + V A^{-1} U)^{-1} V A^{-1} \] for appropriate matrix dimensions.

In our case, let: \(A = \sigma^2 I\), \(U = X\), \(C = C\) and \(V = X^T\). We can then simplify:

3.2.5.1 Posterior Mean Matrix:

\[ \Lambda = C X^T (X C X^T + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} \] can be rewritten as: \[ \Lambda = (C^{-1} + \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T X)^{-1} \cdot \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T \]

3.2.5.2 Posterior Covariance:

\[ C^* = C - C X^T (X C X^T + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} X C \] can be rewritten as: \[ C^* = (C^{-1} + \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T X)^{-1} \]

These are often preferred in implementations, especially when \(p\) (number of predictors) is small compared to \(n\) (number of observations), since they involve inverting \(p \times p\) matrices instead of \(n \times n\) matrices.

3.2.6 Summary

  • The posterior mean becomes: \[ m^* = (C^{-1} + \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T X)^{-1} \left( C^{-1} m + \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T y \right) \]

  • The posterior covariance becomes: \[ C^* = (C^{-1} + \tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T X)^{-1} \]

This formulation highlights how the posterior combines prior precision (\(C^{-1}\)) and data precision (\(\tfrac{1}{\sigma^2} X^T X\)).

3.2.7 Optional Convex Combination (Heuristic)

A simple heuristic can be used to approximate the posterior mean as a convex combination of the prior mean and the OLS estimate,

\[ m^* \approx \alpha \cdot m + (1 - \alpha) \cdot \hat{b}_{\text{OLS}} \]

where \(\hat{b}_{\text{OLS}} = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y\), and the shrinkage factor \(\alpha\) depends on the relative strength of the prior and the data. This expression helps illustrate the idea that Bayesian estimation shrinks the data-driven estimate toward the prior mean.

3.3 Options in the lmbayes package

There are different options with the lmbayes package:

Use the prior from above for fitime.earlying the model to the early data:

lmb1 <- lmb(height ~ age + I(age^2), data=this.early, prior=pr0)
lmb1

height ~ age + I(age^2)

     70.867       8.193      -0.109 

$C

(Intercept)      6.4825 -0.7858  0.03242
age             -0.7858  1.0359 -0.03229
I(age^2)         0.0324 -0.0323  0.00129

$sd
[1] 2.55
lmb1$posterior
$m
(Intercept)         age    I(age^2) 
     70.621       9.059      -0.136 

$C
            (Intercept)      age  I(age^2)
(Intercept)      1.2368 -0.44453  0.016320
age             -0.4445  0.21510 -0.008610
I(age^2)         0.0163 -0.00861  0.000599

$sd
[1] 1.79

Notice that sd changes from the prior to the posterior although we have not specified a prior for sd. The updated sd is based on the residual sum of squares. Setime.earlying update.sd=FALSE means that sd is not updated.

We can make a cheaper update of \(m\) as a convex combination of the prior mean and the OLS estimate of the early data. This is done by setime.earlying alpha to a value between 0 and 1. The update is then

\[ \tilde{m} = \alpha \cdot m + (1 - \alpha) \cdot \hat{\beta}_{ols} \]

This gives no posterior variance matrix, but only the “posterior” mean. As such the prior need only the mean m.

lmb2 <- lmb(height ~ age + I(age^2), data=this.early, prior=list(m=m), alpha=0.4)
lmb2
Bayesian linear model object
height ~ age + I(age^2)
[1] 67.440 11.534 -0.588
lmb2$prior
$m
(Intercept)         age    I(age^2) 
     70.867       8.193      -0.109 
lmb2$posterior
$m
(Intercept)         age    I(age^2) 
     67.440      11.534      -0.588

For benchmarking we can fit a model to all the data using ols. We also fit a model to the early data using ols. This can be done using the lmb function with no prior specified.

bench <- lmb(height ~ age + I(age^2), data=this)
early <- lmb(height ~ age + I(age^2), data=this.early)

We can now compare the predictions from the different models.

this <- this |> add_pred(bench, "bench")
this <- this |> add_pred(early, "early")
this <- this |> add_pred(lmb1, "lmb1")
this <- this |> add_pred(lmb2, "lmb2")
this.long <- this |> pivot_longer(-c(gender, age, subject, height))
this.long |> ggplot(aes(x=age)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = time.early) + 
    geom_point(aes(y=height)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = value, color = name, linetype = name), linewidth = 1)

4 Insights and Interpretation

  • The prior is estimated from training children.
  • The Bayesian prediction (blue) shrinks the early OLS estimate toward the prior.
  • The strength of the prior (\(\alpha\)) controls how much the posterior follows the prior.
  • When early data is sparse, shrinkage improves stability.
